  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong consensus that money laundering is against the law in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity that involves the process of making illegally gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nLaws against money laundering are rooted in the need to combat organized crime, corruption, drug trafficking, terrorism financing, and other illegal activities. The international community has established various frameworks and agreements to combat money laundering, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIn the United States, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act are key pieces of legislation that address money laundering. In the European Union, directives such as the Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD) provide a regulatory framework for member states.\n\nViolations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including heavy fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences. Financial institutions and individuals are required to report suspicious activities that may indicate money laundering, and failure to comply with these legal obligations can also result in significant penalties.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is illegal and widely condemned across the globe, with robust legal frameworks in place to detect, prevent, and punish this illicit activity.",
